Paul Herman, News24Anglican Archbishop Emeritus Desmond Tutu. (Dennis Farrell, AP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - A Palestinian film director has sent a touching letter to Archbishop Emeritus Desmond Tutu, praying for his recovery, and thanking him for supporting the Free Palestine movement.Tutu has been recovering in a Cape Town hospital from an unspecified infection since August 26. The 84-year-old admitted himself to hospital, daughter Thandeka had said.Emad Burnat, an Oscar-nominated filmmaker from Palestine, is in South Africa attending a UN media seminar in Pretoria, and took the chance to write to the Arch.&ldquo;I am just an ordinary Palestinian who once had the humble privilege of meeting you,&rdquo; he wrote.&ldquo;I clearly recall the day you visited our small village of Bil'in in Palestine.&ldquo;I am finally in your beautiful country!&rdquo;'Inspired mothers, fathers and kids'The 5 Broken Cameras director praised Tutu for embracing "frailty" more graciously than most, and said he and his village were praying for his recovery.&ldquo;You have done so much for our cause and struggle, given hope to so many of our mothers, fathers and children and you have inspired generations of our younger activists.&ldquo;Palestine and we Palestinians will be free and your contribution toward our freedom will go down in history books.&rdquo;Burnat said he was touched by South Africa's vibrant diversity and democracy which, with all its problems, was Palestine's beacon of hope.&ldquo;I am deeply inspired and motivated by the various activists, solidarity organisations and the work of the BDS [boycott, divestment, and sanctions] movement in this country.&ldquo;While you were with us you explained how you recognised Israel's system of oppression as being similar to the Apartheid regime.&ldquo;The world is a better place because of you.&rdquo; 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.